# -*- mode:org;coding:utf-8 -*-
#+TITLE: interactors — unify every interaction loop on INTERACTOR-LOOP
#+AUTHOR: Pascal J. Bourguignon

The general mechanism proposed in =issues/open/interactors.lisp= (now
realised as the =clautolisp/autolisp-interactor= subsystem, package
=clautolisp.interactor=) gives every interaction loop one implementation:
a stack of INTERACTOR objects (name, status, prompt, reader, evaluator,
system + user command dictionaries) driven by a single INTERACTOR-LOOP.
Commands are searched down =*interactor-stack*= — user dictionaries first,
inner loops shadowing outer loops — and =NAME CMD …= routes to the named
interactor anywhere on the stack.

* Done (1.4.33–1.4.35)

- The framework itself: command dictionaries (moved out of
  =autolisp-debug-ui='s command-table and generalised, with aliases and
  the =(&whole arg)= raw-argument convention), the typed-token command
  parser (=parse-command=: ident/integer/float/string/token, lenient
  mode for raw arguments embedding Lisp forms), the two readers
  (=comma-command-read=, =command-read=), the interactor struct + stack
  + resolution (user-first, longest phrase, name routing),
  =call-command= (marshaling, prompting for missing required
  arguments), =interactor-loop= / =interactor-return=, and the
  =define-interactor= / =define-command= / =define-user-command= sugar.
  Unit-tested (=clautolisp/autolisp-interactor/tests=).
- The ALDO vocabulary: every command-reference §0 built-in is a
  dictionary command in =*aldo-commands*= (dumb-ui commands.lisp), with
  the =,word= spellings as aliases; user commands live in the separate
  global dictionary and may shadow built-ins; =debugger TOKEN= reaches
  the built-in meaning.
- The Lisp REPL is an interactor (=*autolisp*=, tools/clautolisp):
  =,date= =,uptime= =,help= =,quit= comma-commands through
  =comma-command-read= + =find-and-run-command=; the balanced AutoLISP
  source reader is its sexp fallback.
- NAV: =aldo CMD= / =debug CMD= route explicitly to the debugger (the
  prefix EDIT already had).
- Escape systematisation (1.4.36): interactors carry one optional *alias*
  (=aldo= / =debug= are name and alias of the debugger); =NAME CMD=
  dispatches normally (user table, then system table); the reserved word
  =command= — bare or after the name, like bash's =command foo= — skips
  the user tables (=command CMD=, =aldo command CMD=), which is how a
  shadowing user command calls the system command. =debugger CMD= kept as
  the historical equivalent.

* Done (continued) — the loop unification (1.4.39)

- INTERACTOR-LOOP now drives the debugger stop loop (DBG>), the form
  navigator (NAVI), the flat line navigator (LAVI), the inspector
  (INSPECT>) and the REPL's outer loop. Framework additions: a per-
  instance STATE slot (dictionaries stay shared singletons; entering a
  mode pushes a fresh instance — recursion-safe), *COMMAND-INTERACTOR*
  (a command body reaches its mode's state), ON-RESULT on the OWNING
  interactor (the debugger's carries a command's non-NIL value — a
  resume directive — out with INTERACTOR-RETURN, from however deep a
  mode it was typed in; directives cascade through nested loops), and
  the loop's :FLOOR (the auto-opened navigator pops back to the DBG>
  prompt within the same loop).
- Every interactor is now DECLARED with the framework forms (1.4.41):
  DEFINE-INTERACTOR templates =*aldo*= (alias =debug=) / =*navi*= /
  =*lavi*= / =*inspi*= in dumb-ui (and =*autolisp*= in the tool);
  entering a mode COPY-INTERACTORs its template and fills the per-entry
  slots (state, closures over the UI/stop); the DEFINE-*-COMMAND mode
  macros are sugar over the framework's DEFINE-COMMAND on those
  templates.
- The NAVI / LAVI motion vocabularies and the INSPECT commands are real
  dictionaries (dumb-ui commands.lisp) stacked over the debugger's:
  fall-through, =aldo CMD= routing and =command CMD= user-skipping now
  come from the framework resolution, not hand-coded arms. ±N reads as
  the =skip= command. The inspector implements the §8 example: its =b=
  (bind) shadows the global break; unshadowed debugger verbs (including
  =c=) work while inspecting, and a bare =(FORM)= evaluates with =$=.
- The REPL: ,quit / (quit) leave via INTERACTOR-RETURN; EOF prints the
  fresh line; a CL error escaping a turn is reported by the loop
  instead of crashing the REPL.

* Remaining

- SEDIT as an interactor — DONE 1.4.47
  (interactor-design-revision.issue step 6): the =*SEDIT*= interactor
  lives in autolisp-sedit (now depending on clautolisp.interactor);
  =sedit-enter= pushes it; CLAL-SEDIT and the NAV->EDIT bridge go
  through it. =sedit-run= / =sedit-command= remain the standalone
  library driver.
- =(clal-define-command "INTERACTOR" …)= — DONE 1.4.44
  (interactor-design-revision.issue step 3): the DEFINE-INTERACTOR
  registry, the =*define-interactor-command-hook*= /
  =*list-interactor-names-hook*= runtime hooks, and the
  CLAL-DEFINE-COMMAND / CLAL-LIST-INTERACTOR-NAMES builtins;
  =clal-define-debugger-command= deprecated.
- Typed command arguments: =parse-command= classifies tokens
  (ident/integer/float/string) but command functions receive plain
  strings for compatibility; a declared lambda-list could request
  converted values.
- The =make-prompt-function= depth-prefixed prompt (=[2]LISP> =) is
  available but unused — DECIDED for now: the spec'd prompts (=DBG>= /
  =NAV>= / =SEDIT>= / =_$=) win; revisit only if recursive debugger
  stops prove confusing.
- Command arguments are now uniformly whitespace-separated: the
  inspector's historical glued forms (=d0=, =e(+ 1 2)=) require the
  space (=d 0=, =e (+ 1 2)=).

* Notes / deviations from the sketch

- =input-command= is a struct, not a =(%command …)= list, so a command
  can never be confused with a typed sexp.
- =command-read= treats *every* line as a command except a =(= form
  (the sketch sent non-alphabetic lines to the Lisp reader, which would
  have broken the =.= =>>= =±N= keys); accordingly =parse-command=
  accepts punctuation / signed-integer command names (only a string
  cannot name one).
- WORDS is the *ordered* word sequence of the command's single long
  name — one phrase — and PHRASE is strictly derived (the words joined
  with spaces) by BIND-COMMAND; no constructor or definer takes a
  phrase argument. (Confirmed design, 2026-07-15: the sketch's separate
  "phrase" parameter (=get me out=) was a misreading of words as
  alternatives; alternative spellings are BIND-COMMAND-ALIAS entries.)
- Each interactor has an =evaluator= slot (the sketch had one global
  =lisp-eval-print=): the REPL evaluates globally, the debugger in the
  selected frame.
